        'The First World War began in 1914 after decades of growing tension among the powerful nations of Europe. Countries had been forming political and military alliances and competing to build up their armies and weapons. This atmosphere of rivalry and suspicion made a major war very likely.\n\nThe immediate cause came on 28 June 1914, when Archduke Franz Ferdinand — the heir to the throne of Austria-Hungary — was assassinated by a Serbian in Sarajevo. Austria-Hungary declared war on Serbia in retaliation. Because of the complex system of alliances that had been formed, this dispute between two countries rapidly pulled in most of Europe. Allied nations rushed to defend their partners, and within weeks the conflict had become a massive "Great War" involving dozens of countries. It eventually lasted more than four years, from 1914 to 1918.',
